# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: load-balancer-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] In computer science, **consistent hashing** is a special kind of hashing technique such that when a hash table is resized, only $n/m$ keys need to be remapped on average where n is the number of keys and m is the number of slots.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing evenly distributes cache keys across shards, even if some of the shards crash or become unavailable.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] In contrast, in most traditional hash tables, a change in the number of array slots causes nearly all keys to be remapped because the mapping between the keys and the slots is defined by a modular operation.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is used by Content Delivery Networks because it is useful for distributing requests for content from a rotating population of web servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Tim Berners-Lee credits consistent hashing algorithms, and Daniel Lewin as their inventor, with solving the slashdotting problem which plagued the World Wide Web in the 1990s.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] The term "consistent hashing" was introduced by David Karger *et al.* at MIT for use in distributed caching, particularly for the web.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] This academic paper from 1997 in Symposium on Theory of Computing introduced the term "consistent hashing" as a way of distributing requests among a changing population of web servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Each slot is then represented by a server in a distributed system or cluster.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] The addition of a server and the removal of a server (during scalability or outage) requires only $num\_keys/num\_slots$ items to be re-shuffled when the number of slots (i.e. servers) change.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] The authors mention linear hashing and its ability to handle sequential server addition and removal, while consistent hashing allows servers to be added and removed in an arbitrary order.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] The paper was later re-purposed to address technical challenge of keeping track of a file in peer-to-peer networks such as a distributed hash table.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Teradata used this technique in their distributed database, released in 1986, although they did not use this term.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Teradata still uses the concept of a hash table to fulfill exactly this purpose.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Akamai Technologies was founded in 1998 by the scientists Daniel Lewin and F.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Thomson Leighton (co-authors of the article coining "consistent hashing").
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] In Akamai's content delivery network, consistent hashing is used to balance the load within a cluster of servers, while a stable marriage algorithm is used to balance load across clusters.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing has also been used to reduce the impact of partial system failures in large web applications to provide robust caching without incurring the system-wide fallout of a failure.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing is also the cornerstone of distributed hash tables (DHTs), which employ hash values to partition a keyspace across a distributed set of nodes, then construct an overlay network of connected nodes that provide efficient node retrieval by key.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique .
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] It achieves the goals of consistent hashing using the very different highest random weight (HRW) algorithm.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] However, when a server is added or removed during outage or scaling (when n changes), all the BLOBs in every server should be reassigned and moved due to rehashing, but this operation is expensive.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Consistent hashing was designed to avoid the problem of having to reassign every BLOB when a server is added or removed throughout the cluster.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] The central idea is to use a hash function that maps both the BLOB and servers to a unit circle, usually $2\pi$ radians.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] For example, $\zeta =\Phi \ \%\ 360$ (where $\Phi$ is hash of a BLOB or server's identifier, like IP address or UUID).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Each BLOB is then assigned to the next server that appears on the circle in clockwise order.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] This provides an even distribution of BLOBs to servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] But, more importantly, if a server fails and is removed from the circle, only the BLOBs that were mapped to the failed server need to be reassigned to the next server in clockwise order.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Likewise, if a new server is added, it is added to the unit circle, and only the BLOBs mapped to that server need to be reassigned.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Importantly, when a server is added or removed, the vast majority of the BLOBs maintain their prior server assignments, and the addition of $n^{th}$ server only causes $1/n$ fraction of the BLOBs to relocate.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Although the process of moving BLOBs across cache servers in the cluster depends on the context, commonly, the newly added cache server identifies its "predecessor" and moves all the BLOBs, whose mapping belongs to this server (i.e. whose hash value is less than that of the new server), from it.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] However, in the case of web page caches, in most implementations there is no involvement of moving or copying, assuming the cached BLOB is small enough.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] When a request hits a newly added cache server, a cache miss happens and a request to the actual web server is made and the BLOB is cached locally for future requests.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] The redundant BLOBs on the previously used cache servers would be removed as per the cache eviction policies.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Let $h_{b}(x)$ and $h_{s}(x)$ be the hash functions used for the BLOB and server's unique identifier respectively.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] In practice, a binary search tree (BST) is used to dynamically maintain the ${\text{server ID}}$ within a cluster or hashring, and to find the successor or minimum within the BST, tree traversal is used.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] To avoid skewness of multiple nodes within the radian, which happen due to lack of uniform distribution of the servers within the cluster, multiple labels are used.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Those duplicate labels are called "virtual nodes" i.e. multiple labels which point to a single "real" label or server within the cluster.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] The amount of virtual nodes or duplicate labels used for a particular server within a cluster is called the "weight" of that particular server.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] A number of extensions to the basic technique are needed for effectively using consistent hashing for load balancing in practice.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] In the basic scheme above, if a server fails, all its BLOBs are reassigned to the next server in clockwise order, potentially doubling the load of that server.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] To ensure a more even redistribution of BLOBs on server failure, each server can be hashed to multiple locations on the unit circle.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] When a server fails, the BLOBs assigned to each of its replicas on the unit circle will get reassigned to a different server in clockwise order, thus redistributing the BLOBs more evenly.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Another extension concerns a situation where a single BLOB gets "hot" and is accessed a large number of times and will have to be hosted in multiple servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] In this situation, the BLOB may be assigned to multiple contiguous servers by traversing the unit circle in clockwise order.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] A more complex practical consideration arises when two BLOBs are hashed near each other in the unit circle and both get "hot" at the same time.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] In this case, both BLOBs will use the same set of contiguous servers in the unit circle.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] This situation can be ameliorated by each BLOB choosing a different hash function for mapping servers to the unit circle.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Rendezvous hashing, designed in 1996, is a simpler and more general technique, and permits fully distributed agreement on a set of k options out of a possible set of n options.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] It can in fact be shown that consistent hashing is a special case of rendezvous hashing.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] Because of its simplicity and generality, rendezvous hashing is now being used in place of Consistent Hashing in many applications.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] If key values will always increase monotonically, an alternative approach using a hash table with monotonic keys may be more suitable than consistent hashing.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/consistent-hashing] The $O(K/N)$ is an average cost for redistribution of keys and the $O(\log N)$ complexity for consistent hashing comes from the fact that a binary search among nodes angles is required to find the next node on the ring.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A **network switch** (also called **switching hub**, **bridging hub**, **Ethernet switch**, and—by the IEEE—**MAC bridge**) is networking hardware that connects devices on a computer network by using packet switching to receive and forward data to the destination device.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A network switch is a multiport network bridge that uses MAC addresses to forward data at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Some switches can also forward data at the network layer (layer 3) by additionally incorporating routing functionality.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Such switches are commonly known as layer-3 switches or multilayer switches.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Switches for Ethernet are the most common form of network switch.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] The first MAC Bridge was invented in 1983 by Mark Kempf, an engineer in the Networking Advanced Development group of Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] The first two-port bridge product (LANBridge 100) was introduced by that company shortly after.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] The company subsequently produced multi-port switches for both Ethernet and FDDI.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] DEC decided to license its MAC Bridge patent on a royalty-free, non-discriminatory basis that allowed IEEE standardization.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] This permitted a number of other companies to produce multi-port switches, including Kalpana.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Ethernet was initially a shared-access medium, but the introduction of the MAC bridge began its transformation into its most-common point-to-point form without a collision domain.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Switches also exist for other types of networks, including Fibre Channel, Asynchronous Transfer Mode, and InfiniBand.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Unlike repeater hubs, which broadcast the same data out of each port and let the devices pick out the data addressed to them, a network switch learns the Ethernet addresses of connected devices and then only forwards data to the port connected to the device to which it is addressed.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A switch is a device in a computer network that connects other devices together.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Multiple data cables are plugged into a switch to enable communication between different networked devices.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Switches manage the flow of data across a network by transmitting a received network packet only to the one or more devices for which the packet is intended.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Each networked device connected to a switch can be identified by its network address, allowing the switch to direct the flow of traffic, maximizing the security and efficiency of the network.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A switch is more intelligent than an Ethernet hub, which simply retransmits packets out of every port of the hub except the port on which the packet was received, unable to distinguish different recipients, and achieves an overall lower network efficiency.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] An Ethernet switch operates at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to create a separate collision domain for each switch port.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Each device connected to a switch port can transfer data to any of the other ports at any time and the transmissions will not interfere.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Because broadcasts are still being forwarded to all connected devices by the switch, the newly formed network segment continues to be a broadcast domain.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Switches may also operate at higher layers of the OSI model, including the network layer and above.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A switch that also operates at these higher layers is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Segmentation involves the use of a switch to split a larger collision domain into smaller ones in order to reduce collision probability and to improve overall network throughput.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] In the extreme case (i.e., micro-segmentation), each device is directly connected to a switch port dedicated to the device.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] In contrast to an Ethernet hub, there is a separate collision domain on each switch port.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] This allows computers to have dedicated bandwidth on point-to-point connections to the network and also to run in full-duplex mode.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Full-duplex mode has only one transmitter and one receiver per collision domain, making collisions impossible.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] The network switch plays an integral role in most modern Ethernet local area networks (LANs).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Mid-to-large-sized LANs contain a number of linked managed switches.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Small office/home office (SOHO) applications typically use a single switch, or an all-purpose device such as a residential gateway to access small office/home broadband services such as DSL or cable Internet.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] In most of these cases, the end-user device contains a router and components that interface to the particular physical broadband technology.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Many switches have pluggable modules, such as Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) modules.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] These modules often contain a transceiver that connects the switch to a physical medium, such as a fiber optic cable.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Alternatively, DAC (Direct Attach Copper) cables may be used in place of modules.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] These modules were preceded by Medium Attachment Units connected via Attachment Unit Interfaces to switches and have evolved over time: the first modules were Gigabit interface converters, followed by XENPAK modules, SFP modules, XFP transceivers, SFP+ modules, QSFP, QSFP-DD, and OSFP modules.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Pluggable modules are also used for transmitting video in broadcast applications.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] CPO is also considerably easier to adapt to water cooling.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Switches are most commonly used as the network connection point for hosts at the edge of a network.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] In the hierarchical internetworking model and similar network architectures, switches are also used deeper in the network to provide connections between the switches at the edge.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] In switches intended for commercial use, built-in or modular interfaces make it possible to connect different types of networks, including Ethernet, Fibre Channel, RapidIO, ATM, ITU-T G.hn and 802.11.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] This connectivity can be at any of the layers mentioned.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] While the layer-2 functionality is adequate for bandwidth-shifting within one technology, interconnecting technologies such as Ethernet and Token Ring is performed more easily at layer 3 or via routing.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Devices that interconnect at the layer 3 are traditionally called routers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Where there is a need for a great deal of analysis of network performance and security, switches may be connected between WAN routers as places for analytic modules.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Some vendors provide firewall, network intrusion detection, and performance analysis modules that can plug into switch ports.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Some of these functions may be on combined modules.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Through port mirroring, a switch can create a mirror image of data that can go to an external device, such as intrusion detection systems and packet sniffers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A modern switch may implement power over Ethernet (PoE), which avoids the need for attached devices, such as a VoIP phone or wireless access point, to have a separate power supply.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Because switches can have their power circuits connected to uninterruptible power supplies, the connected device can continue operating even when regular office power fails.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] In 1989 and 1990, Kalpana introduced the first multiport Ethernet switch, its seven-port EtherSwitch.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Modern commercial switches primarily use Ethernet interfaces.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] The core function of an Ethernet switch is to provide multiple ports of layer-2 bridging.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Layer-1 functionality is required in all switches in support of the higher layers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Many switches also perform operations at other layers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A device capable of more than bridging is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A layer 2 network device is a multiport device that uses hardware addresses (MAC addresses) to process and forward data at the data link layer (layer 2).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] A switch operating as a network bridge may interconnect otherwise separate layer 2 networks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] The bridge learns the MAC address of each connected device, storing this data in a table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] This table is often implemented using high-speed content-addressable memory (CAM), some vendors refer to the MAC address table as a CAM table.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Bridges also buffer an incoming packet and adapt the transmission speed to that of the outgoing port.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] While there are specialized applications, such as storage area networks, where the input and output interfaces are the same bandwidth, this is not always the case in general LAN applications.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] In LANs, a switch used for end-user access typically concentrates lower bandwidth and uplinks into a higher bandwidth.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] The Ethernet header at the start of the frame contains all the information required to make a forwarding decision; some high-performance switches can begin forwarding the frame to the destination whilst still receiving the frame payload from the sender.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] This cut-through switching can significantly reduce latency through the switch.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Interconnects between switches may be regulated using the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) that disables forwarding on links so that the resulting local area network is a tree without switching loops.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] In contrast to routers, spanning tree bridges must have topologies with only one active path between two points.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Shortest path bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) are layer 2 alternatives to STP, which allow all paths to be active with multiple equal cost paths.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Rack-mounted switches may be stand-alone units, stackable switches or large chassis units with swappable line cards.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] It is difficult to monitor traffic that is bridged using a switch because only the sending and receiving ports can see the traffic.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] These monitoring features are rarely present on consumer-grade switches.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/network-switch] Other monitoring methods include connecting a layer-1 hub or network tap between the monitored device and its switch port.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] In its simplest implementation, round-robin DNS works by responding to DNS requests not only with a single potential IP address, but with a list of potential IP addresses corresponding to several servers that host identical services.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] The order in which IP addresses from the list are returned is the basis for the term *round robin*.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] With each DNS response, the IP address sequence in the list is permuted.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Traditionally, IP clients initially attempt connections with the first address returned from a DNS query, so that on different connection attempts, clients would receive service from different providers, thus distributing the overall load among servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Some resolvers attempt to re-order the list to give priority to numerically "closer" networks.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] This behaviour was standardized in RFC 3484 during the definition of IPv6.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] When applied to IPv4, a bug in Windows Vista caused issues and defeated round-robin load-balancing.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Some desktop clients do try alternate addresses after a connection timeout of up to 30 seconds.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS is often used to load balance requests among a number of web servers.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] For example, a company has one domain name and three identical copies of the same web site residing on three servers with three IP addresses.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] The DNS server will be set up so that domain name has multiple A records, one for each IP address.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] When one user accesses the home page it will be sent to the first IP address.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] The second user who accesses the home page will be sent to the next IP address, and the third user will be sent to the third IP address.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] In each case, once the IP address is given out, it goes to the end of the list.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] The fourth user, therefore, will be sent to the first IP address, and so forth.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] A round-robin DNS name is, on rare occasions, referred to as a "rotor" due to the rotation among alternative A records.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Although easy to implement, round-robin DNS has a number of drawbacks, such as those arising from record caching in the DNS hierarchy itself, as well as client-side address caching and reuse, the combination of which can be difficult to manage.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS should not solely be relied upon for service availability.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] If a service at one of the addresses in the list fails, the DNS will continue to hand out that address and clients will still attempt to reach the inoperable service.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS may not be the best choice for load balancing on its own, since it merely alternates the order of the address records each time a name server is queried.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Because it does not take transaction time, server load, and network congestion into consideration, it works best for services with a large number of uniformly distributed connections to servers of equivalent capacity.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Otherwise, it just does load distribution.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] Methods exist to overcome such limitations.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] For example, modified DNS servers (such as lbnamed) can routinely poll mirrored servers for availability and load factor.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/round-robin-dns] If a server does not reply as required, the server can be temporarily removed from the DNS pool, until it reports that it is once again operating within specs.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Weighted round robin is a generalisation of round-robin scheduling.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Whereas round-robin cycles over the queues or tasks and gives one service opportunity per cycle, weighted round robin offers to each a fixed number of opportunities, as specified by the configured weight, which serves to influence the portion of capacity received by each queue or task.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] In computer networks, a service opportunity is the emission of one packet if the selected queue is non-empty.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] If all packets have the same size, WRR is the simplest approximation of generalized processor sharing (GPS).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] The main ones are the *classical* WRR, and the *interleaved* WRR.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] WRR is presented in the following as a network scheduler.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] It can also be used to schedule tasks in a similar way.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] A weighted round-robin network scheduler has n input queues, $q_{1},...,q_{n}$ .
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] To each queue $q_{i}$ is associated $w_{i}$ , a positive integer, called the *weight*.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] The WRR scheduler has a cyclic behavior.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] In each cycle, each queue $q_{i}$ has $w_{i}$ emissions opportunities.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] The different WRR algorithms differ in the distribution of these opportunities in the cycle.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] In classical WRR the scheduler cycles over the queues.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] When a queue $q_{i}$ is selected, the scheduler will send packets, up to the emission of the $w_{i}$ packet or the end of the queue.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] In IWRR, each cycle is split into $w_{max}$ rounds.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] A queue with weight $w_{i}$ can emit one packet at round r only if $r\leq w_{i}$ .
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Consider a situation where there are 7 packets in the first queue, **A,B,C,D,E,F,G**, 3 in the second queue, **U,V,W** and 2 in the third queue **X,Y**.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Assume that there are no more packet arrivals.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Immediately after the end of transmission of **Y**, the second cycle starts, and **F,G** from $q_{1}$ are transmitted, followed by **W** from $q_{2}$ .
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] With interleaved WRR, the first cycle is split into 5 rounds (since $max(w_{1},w_{2},w_{3})=5$ ).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Then starts the second cycle, where **F,W,G** are sent.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Task or process scheduling can be done in WRR in a way similar to packet scheduling: when considering a set of n active tasks, they are scheduled in a cyclic way, each task $\tau _{i}$ gets $w_{i}$ quantum or slice of processor time .
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Like round-robin, weighted round robin scheduling is simple, easy to implement, work conserving and starvation-free.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] If the queues have packets of variable length, the part of the bandwidth received by each queue depends not only on the weights but also on the packet sizes.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] If a mean packets size $s_{i}$ is known for every queue $q_{i}$ , each queue will receive a long-term part of the bandwidth equal to ${\frac {s_{i}\times w_{i}}{\sum _{j=1}^{n}s_{j}\times w_{j}}}$ .
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Since IWRR has smaller per-class bursts than WRR, it implies smaller worst-case delays.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] WRR for network packet scheduling was first proposed by Katevenis, Sidiropoulos and Courcoubetis in 1991, specifically for scheduling in ATM networks using fixed-size packets (cells).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] The primary limitation of weighted round-robin queuing is that it provides the correct percentage of bandwidth to each service class only if all the packets in all the queues are the same size or if the mean packet size is known in advance.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] In the more general case of IP networks with variable-size packets, to approximate GPS, the weight factors must be adjusted based on the packet size.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] That requires estimation of the average packet size, which makes a good GPS approximation hard to achieve in practice with WRR.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Deficit round robin is a later variation of WRR that achieves better GPS approximation without knowing the mean packet size of each connection in advance.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] More effective scheduling disciplines were also introduced, which handle the limitations mentioned above (e.g., weighted fair queuing).
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Weighted round robin has been adopted by several real-time operating systems (RTOSes) as a task scheduling strategy, where task weights determine the proportion of CPU time allocated to each thread.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] Notable examples include SuperTinyKernel RTOS, a bare-metal C++ RTOS for embedded systems, which implements a *Smooth Weighted Round Robin* (SWRR) strategy.
[src:load-balancer-algorithms/weighted-round-robin] This results in more uniform CPU utilisation and lower scheduling jitter compared to classical WRR, at the cost of a moderately more complex scheduling calculation per context switch.
